{"cursor":"6813","size":14,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name =Mihira Bhoja I birth_place = death_date = 885 death_place = Narmada\n| River reign = 836â885 CE. religion = Hinduism occupation = Gurjar King spouse\n| = parents = Ramabhadra (father) children =\n}} , New Delhi]] 'Mihira Bhoja I' (836â885 CE) or 'Bhoja I' was a ruler of the\nGurjar Pratihara dynasty of India. He succeeded his father Ramabhadra. Bhoja was\na devotee of Vishnu and adopted the title of Adivaraha which is inscribed on\nsome of his coins. One of the outstanding political figures of India\nin ninth century, he ranks with Dhruva Dharavarsha and Dharmapala as a great\ngeneral and empire builder. {{cite book\n | title =History of Ancient India: Earliest Times to 1000 A. D. author = Radhey\n | Shyam Chaurasia publisher =Atlantic Publishers & Distributors year =2002 page\n | =207 id = ISBN 81-269-0027-X,ISBN 978-81-269-0027-5 url\n | =http://books.google.co.in/books?id=cWmsQQ2smXIC&pg=PA207&dq quote=He was\n | undoubtedly one of the outstanding political figures of India in ninth\n | century and ranks with Dhruva and Dharmapala as a great general and empire\n | builder.\n}}\n\nAt its height, Bhoja's empire extended to Narmada River in the South, Sutlej\nRiver in the northwest, and up to Bengal in the east. It extended over a large\narea from the foot of the Himalayas up to the river Narmada and included the\npresent district of Etawah in Uttar Pradesh. [http://etawah.nic.in/gaz/2.htm\nE-gazeteer-History of Etawah district]\n","linknr":189,"url":"Mihira_Bhoja_I","recorded":1375071775,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Mihira_Bhoja_I&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Mihira_Bhoja_I&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&mod